{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_working_tuples",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Working with Tuples",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Now that you know what tuples are, let's learn how to work with them effectively. Tuples have some special features that make them very useful in Python."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You'll learn about unpacking, looping, and useful tuple operations."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "tuple_unpacking",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Tuple Unpacking",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Unpacking** lets you assign each item in a tuple to a separate variable in one line."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "coordinates = (10, 20)\nx, y = coordinates\nprint(f\"x: {x}, y: {y}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "x: 10, y: 20"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The tuple items are automatically assigned to `x` and `y`. This is much cleaner than accessing with indices."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "unpacking_direct",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can also unpack directly without storing the tuple in a variable first."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "name, age, job = (\"Alice\", 25, \"Engineer\")\nprint(f\"{name} is {age} years old\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Alice is 25 years old"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Each value is unpacked into its corresponding variable."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_unpacking",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "code_fill",
                    "content": "Unpack the tuple into separate variables `r`, `g`, and `b`.",
                    "properties": {
